
Triadic Overlap Hypothesis
A speculative framework for recursive stability across systems
Abstract
This hypothesis proposes that many stable systems—biological, cognitive, technological, and social—share a common geometric interaction pattern involving three roles: two sovereign domains and an intermediate translation membrane. Stability emerges when interaction occurs through this membrane rather than through direct coupling between the domains.
When the membrane maintains balanced overlap, the system supports recursive coherence, distributed agency, and resilient feedback loops. When the membrane becomes pinched, bypassed, or hierarchical, instability accumulates through bottlenecks, prediction errors, and asymmetric control structures.
The hypothesis suggests that this triadic geometry of interaction may recur across scales—from neural communication to human-machine interaction to collective social organization.
This document presents the pattern as a geometric speculation, not a claim of universal causation.

1. Core Structural Pattern
The system consists of three distinct domains:
O — Operator / Meaning domain
R — Resonance / Translation membrane
S — Substrate / Structural domain

Constraint:
O ≠ R ≠ S
Interaction(O,S) ⊆ R
Direct coupling(O,S) = prohibited

Meaning and structure do not interact directly; they interact through a membrane that interprets between them.
Examples of this membrane include:
language
interfaces
neural integration layers
governance institutions
conversational space

